<section aria-label="AI as an EAL tool" style="margin-top: 32px;">
  <div class="prose">
    <h2>AI as an EAL tool</h2>
    <p>AI is the most powerful tool an EAL student has — when used openly. Translation (L1 ↔ English), vocabulary explanation in your first language, sentence rewording for clarity, comprehension checks on dense readings, and oral-defense rehearsal in L1 are all <strong>legitimate uses</strong> as long as you document them under the <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation Protocol</a>.</p>
    <p>What's NOT legitimate is asking AI to write the deliverable, submitting AI translation you haven't read, or hiding AI use. These are the same lines as for any student. The <a href="/foundations/eal/teacher-guide/">Teacher Strategy Guide §5</a> spells out the disclosure pattern for EAL-heavy AI use — a worked example is in there.</p>
  </div>
</section>

